      "definition": "A requirement established by law or regulation that an organization must meet, regardless of internal preference or operational convenience.",
      "what_it_really_means": "Not optional. Not a suggestion. The floor set by law. Organizations sometimes treat statutory requirements as targets to hit or miss depending on resources. They are not targets. Missing them has legal, financial, or reputational consequences that internal policy cannot override.",
      "why": "All three components are required. Legal obligation without a defined standard is vague compliance. A defined standard without enforceability is guidance that can be ignored. Enforceability without a legal obligation is internal policy dressed up as law. All three together define what a statutory requirement actually is.",
