      "what_it_really_means": "An idea or creation the organization legally owns. IP is only valuable when it is protected and when someone would pay to use it or be disadvantaged without it. A patent on something no one wants is legally protected trivia. A patent on something the market needs is a competitive moat.",
      "why": "Legal protection and commercial value are grouped because one without the other is incomplete. Original creation without legal protection is an idea anyone can copy. Legal protection without commercial value is an expense that produces no return. Both together define IP that is worth owning, defending, and monetizing.",
