      "definition": "The process of assigning a monetary value to a company's inventory at a point in time, using methods such as FIFO, LIFO, or weighted average cost.",
      "what_it_really_means": "Deciding what the stock is worth on paper. The method chosen affects reported profit. FIFO in a rising cost environment produces higher ending inventory values and lower cost of goods sold, lifting profit. LIFO does the opposite. The physical inventory does not change. The accounting method determines what the financial statements show.",
      "why": "Cost method applied and market adjustment are grouped because both shape the final valuation. The cost method determines the base value from historical cost. The market adjustment applies when inventory has declined in value below cost, requiring a write-down to the lower of cost or market. Both are required for an accurate balance sheet representation.",
