      "definition": "A business or pricing model in which access to a product, software, or intellectual property is granted through a formal license agreement rather than outright purchase.",
      "what_it_really_means": "You pay to use it, not to own it. License-based models give the licensor ongoing control over the product while generating recurring revenue. The licensee gets access without the cost or responsibility of ownership. The terms of the license determine almost everything: what you can do, for how long, and what happens if you stop paying.",
      "why": "Defined terms and fee structure are grouped because a license without both is incomplete as a commercial arrangement. Terms without a fee structure describe conditions with no economics. A fee structure without defined terms is pricing without boundaries on use. Together they constitute the license as a functional business agreement.",
