      "what_it_really_means": "Two organizations becoming one. Mergers are usually framed as equal partnerships and are rarely experienced that way. The larger organization's culture, systems, and leadership typically dominate. The value case rests on synergies — cost savings, revenue opportunities, or capability combinations — that must be realized through integration to justify the disruption. Many mergers fail to deliver the projected value.",
      "why": "Combination into a single organization and negotiated terms and ownership structure are grouped because a merger is defined by both as a legal and commercial event. Two entities without the formal combination remain separate organizations with a relationship. Combination without negotiated terms and ownership structure is acquisition by attrition rather than merger by agreement. Together they define the merger as a structured, consensual unification.",
