      "definition": "A structured evaluation process that uses multiple exercises and trained assessors to assess candidates or employees against defined competencies, typically used for selection or development.",
      "what_it_really_means": "A deeper look at how someone actually behaves, not just what they say about themselves. Assessment centers test candidates through simulations, role plays, group exercises, and structured interviews. The multiple exercises and multiple assessors reduce the bias of any single observation. The behavioral evidence produced is more predictive of job performance than interviews alone.",
      "why": "Trained assessors and behavioral observation against defined competencies are grouped because an assessment center without both is a collection of exercises rather than a structured evaluation. Trained assessors ensure consistent observation and calibrated judgment. Behavioral observation against defined competencies ensures the evaluation is measuring what it claims to measure. Together they define an assessment process that produces defensible, comparable conclusions.",
