      "definition": "A sequence of tasks or process steps that are executed automatically by software in response to defined triggers, reducing manual effort and increasing consistency and speed.",
      "what_it_really_means": "The process runs itself. Automated workflows replace repetitive human tasks with software logic that executes reliably and at scale. Invoice approvals, onboarding sequences, data entry, and notification routing are common examples. Automation reduces errors, speeds up cycle times, and frees people for work that requires judgment. It also amplifies any errors built into the process it automates.",
      "why": "Trigger-based execution and minimal human intervention are grouped because automated workflow is defined by both. Defined process steps without triggers require someone to initiate each run. Triggers without minimal human intervention produce automated initiation of a process that still requires manual completion. Together they define automation that actually removes human effort from the execution of repetitive, rule-based work.",
