      "definition": "The ability of different systems, applications, or organizations to work together and exchange information in a way that each can use.",
      "what_it_really_means": "They can talk to each other and actually understand the conversation. Interoperability is a persistent challenge in healthcare, government, and enterprise technology. Systems that cannot interoperate force manual data transfer, create silos, and produce inconsistent information across platforms. The challenge is not always technical. Sometimes systems could be made to interoperate but organizations choose not to.",
      "why": "The ability to exchange and use data is the critical qualifier. Connection without usable exchange is interface-level integration with no practical value. Two systems that can send data back and forth but cannot interpret each other's formats have achieved communication without comprehension. The formula captures both the technical connection and the practical outcome it must produce.",
