      "definition": "A formally published specification or guideline developed by the International Organization for Standardization that defines best practices, requirements, or benchmarks for products, services, or systems.",
      "what_it_really_means": "A globally recognized standard for how something should be done or made. ISO standards exist across industries: quality management, environmental management, information security, food safety, and hundreds of others. Certification to an ISO standard signals to customers, regulators, and partners that the organization meets a verified, internationally recognized bar.",
      "why": "Defined compliance requirements and third-party certification pathway are grouped because the ISO standard derives its value from both. A specification without defined requirements cannot be audited. Requirements without a certification pathway produce self-assessment rather than independent verification. Both together are what make ISO certification meaningful to parties outside the organization.",
