      "components": [
        "total engagement actions",
        "total audience or impressions"
      ],
      "definition": "The percentage of an audience that actively interacts with content, a campaign, or a product relative to the total number exposed to it.",
      "what_it_really_means": "How many people who saw it actually did something. Engagement rate distinguishes active response from passive exposure. A million impressions with a 0.1% engagement rate and a thousand impressions with a 10% engagement rate produce the same number of engaged people but very different signals about content effectiveness. Rate matters more than volume for understanding whether content is resonating.",
      "why": "Ratio formula. Total engagement actions alone is a count that cannot be evaluated without scale context. Total audience or impressions alone is reach without response. Divided, they produce a rate that makes comparison meaningful across campaigns, content types, and time periods. The definition of engagement varies by platform and context — clicks, shares, comments, likes — and the rate is only comparable when the engagement definition is consistent.",
