      "what_it_really_means": "How good the predictions actually were. Forecast accuracy is both a performance metric and a diagnostic. Low accuracy signals that the forecasting inputs, assumptions, or methodology are unreliable. Tracking accuracy over time reveals whether the organization is getting better at forecasting or consistently biased in one direction — almost always optimistic. Systematic optimism in forecasts is a cultural problem as much as a technical one.",
      "why": "Ratio formula. Actual result divided by forecasted result produces a percentage — 100% means the forecast was exact, below means it over-projected, above means it under-projected. Both parts are required. Actual result without a forecast has no reference. A forecast without an actual result has not yet been tested. Together they define accuracy as the relationship between prediction and reality over time.",
