      "definition": "A three-stage change management model developed by Kurt Lewin that describes the process of moving an organization from its current state through transition to a new, stable state.",
      "what_it_really_means": "You cannot change what is frozen, and change that is not anchored will revert. Lewin's model is one of the oldest and most enduring frameworks in change management. Unfreeze challenges the status quo and creates motivation to change. Change implements the new behaviors, processes, or structures. Refreeze solidifies the change so it becomes the new normal. Organizations that skip refreezing find the change fades and the old way reasserts itself.",
      "why": "All three components are required and sequential. Unfreeze without change creates disruption with no resolution. Change without unfreeze encounters a system that resists because no one prepared it to move. Change without refreeze produces a temporary shift that reverts when attention moves elsewhere. Together they define a complete change cycle that produces durable rather than temporary transformation.",
