      "what_it_really_means": "Renting without recording the obligation as debt. Under older accounting standards, operating leases kept liabilities off the balance sheet, which made leveraged organizations appear less indebted. Modern accounting standards — IFRS 16 and ASC 842 — require most leases to appear on the balance sheet, narrowing the distinction between operating and finance leases for reporting purposes.",
      "why": "Off-balance-sheet treatment under older standards and lease payments as operating expense are grouped because they defined the commercial and accounting appeal of the operating lease model. The off-balance-sheet treatment reduced apparent leverage. Expensing payments through the income statement rather than amortizing an asset produced a different earnings profile. Both together defined why organizations preferred operating leases and why accounting standards were eventually changed.",
