      "what_it_really_means": "How much revenue growth flows to profit. High operating leverage means a large proportion of costs are fixed. When revenue grows, those fixed costs are already covered and most of the additional revenue becomes profit. When revenue falls, the fixed costs remain and losses accumulate quickly. Operating leverage amplifies both directions. It is the structural reason some businesses are highly profitable in good times and highly fragile in bad ones.",
      "why": "Ratio formula. Fixed costs in the numerator relative to total costs produces the leverage ratio. A high ratio means the cost structure is predominantly fixed. A low ratio means variable costs dominate and the business scales more linearly. The ratio does not indicate whether high or low leverage is better — that depends on the revenue stability and growth trajectory of the business.",
