      "what_it_really_means": "How often it works. Success rate is one of the most broadly applicable metrics in business — from sales close rates to software test pass rates to clinical trial outcomes. Its value depends entirely on how success is defined and whether that definition is consistent across what is being measured. A rising success rate on a trivially easy standard means less than a stable success rate on a genuinely demanding one.",
      "why": "Ratio formula. Successful outcomes alone is a count without context. Total attempts alone is volume without result. Divided, they produce a rate that can be tracked, compared, and improved. The rate is what makes success meaningful as a metric rather than just a number — it tells you how reliably success is being produced relative to the effort being applied.",
