      "definition": "A growth pattern in which each new user generates more than one additional user through sharing, referral, or word of mouth, producing exponential expansion without proportional marketing spend.",
      "what_it_really_means": "The product spreads itself. Viral growth occurs when the average user brings in more than one new user — a viral coefficient above one. Below one, the product still grows but at a decelerating rate. Above one, it accelerates. True viral growth is rare and often temporary. Most products described as going viral experienced a spike rather than sustained compounding. The distinction matters for planning.",
      "why": "Referral or sharing mechanism and viral coefficient above one are grouped because viral growth requires both as structural conditions. An existing user base without a sharing mechanism does not spread organically. A sharing mechanism without a coefficient above one produces word of mouth that does not compound. Together they define the conditions for growth that self-accelerates rather than growth that requires continued marketing investment to sustain.",
